 Geoderma, 34 (1984) 43--68                                                      43  Elsevier Science Publishers B.V., Amsterdam -- Printed in The Netherlands    EXPERIMENTAL STUDY OF SOIL MICROFABRICS INDUCED BY  ISOTROPIC STRESSES OF WETTING AND DRYING    J.B. DALRYMPLE and C.Y. JIM*~  Department of Soil Science, University of Reading, Reading (Great Britain)  (Received June 15, 1983; accepted after revision June 11, 1984)    ABSTRACT    Dalrymple, J.B. and Jim, C.Y., 1984. Experimental study of soil microfabrics induced  by isotropic stresses of wetting and drying. Geoderma, 34: 43--68.    This experimental study examines the relationship between texture and microfabric  under isotropic stresses generated by wetting and drying. This can be achieved by  observing and measuring the reorganization of microfabrics (plasmic fabrics and related  distribution pattern, RDP). Microfabrics are produced in the laboratory by mixing  montmorillonite with various proportions of sand and silt, and subjecting them to wetting  and drying without confinement. Thin sections axe cut to study their microfabrics.  Results show broad and systematic variations in fabric with changes in texture. Fine  matrix (silt plus clay in physical continuity) is developed in samples with low sand:silt  ratio, and regardless of this ratio at high clay levels. Coarse porphyric and fine porphyric  RDP are formed at low and high clay contents, respectively. Plasmic fabrics are repre-  sented mainly by insepic and weakly developed mosepic and masepic fabrics in the matrix  in the form of small plasma separations with random orientation, and weak skelsepic  plasma as embedded grain argillans. On the other hand, coarse matrix (sand grains in  physical continuity) dominates the sandy samples which are associated with relatively  thick and strongly birefringent free grain argillans giving wall-developed skelsepic fabric.  The RDP follows two major paths: beginning with orthogranic (very low clay content)  along the iunctic sequence at low clay:silt ratio and along the chlamydic sequence at high  ratio. The regularities in fabric development are interpreted in the light of the dynamic  properties and behaviour of the active clay fraction in a clay--water system. The  pedogenetic implications of the results are explored, and the term "erdic" fabric defined.    INTRODUCTION    Among the suite of fundamental soil processes subsumed under erdefica-  tion (Conacher and Dalrymple, 1977), wetting and drying is perhaps the  most important. It is its influence under an overall isotropic stress regime on  the micromorphological organization of soil materials with different texture  that constitutes the theme of the present study.    *~ Present address: Department of Geography and Geology, University of Hong Kong,  Pokfulam Road, Hong Kong.    0016-7061/84/$03.00     1984 Elsevier Science Publishers B.V.    44  =  Eswaran and Banos (1976) have provided a conceptual treatment to the  general thesis that relates fabric to texture and, although the subsequent  empirical investigations by Brewer (1979) and McKeague and Guertin (1982)  show that a broad relationship does exist, many aberrant cases were found to  occur. Thus, in order to avoid the uncertainty and conjecture involved in the  conventional empirical approach where both processes and historical recon-  struction of micromorphological reorganization are inferred from responses  (Brewer, 1972a, b), an experimental approach is adopted. This follows the  few, but notable examples in the work of Kubiena (1938), Day and  Holmgren (1952), Brewer and Haldane (1957), Bartelli and OdeU (1960),  Buol and Hole (1961), Wells (1965), Dijkerman et al. (1967), Dalrymple  (1972) and Wilke and Schwertmann (1978). Even so, many of the recent  advances on the colloidal properties and behaviour of clay minerals with a  clay--water system have yet to be translated into working hypotheses to  explain the organization of fabric units in soils. Thus, as there is little sound  knowledge as to what fabric features result from or are modified by what  pedogenetic processes, rigorous testing is necessary. In this case experimental  evidence is obtained on the relationship between the characteristics of soil  microfabrics -- related distribution pattern (RDP) and plasmic fabric (Brewer,  1964) -- and the behaviour of the constituents making up the elementary  fabric units. It is intended to test the hypothesis that the activity and  malleability, and hence the mobility, of the clay fraction operating in a low  moisture clay--water system is the prime agent in the moulding of fabric  units in the soil environment. If so, the reorganization of soil microfabrics  induced by isotropic stresses of wetting and drying could lead to the  establishment and definition of an "erdic" fabric.    EXPERIMENTAL PROCEDURES    Wyoming bentonite (BDH) was dispersed in deionized water and the  &lt;2gm e.s.d, fraction separated by gravity sedimentation. Calcium and  sodium clays were prepared by flocculating the clay in suspension with  appropriate chloride solutions, followed by three washings with molar  chloride solutions by centrifugation and decantation. The resulting homo-  ionic clays were washed repeatedly until free from chloride. In addition the  sodium clay was washed thrice with deionized water and thereafter with  industrial methylated spirit (IMS), in order to suppress spontaneous disper-  sion as the electrolyte concentration of the pore fluid was progressively  reduced. The replacement of interstitial pore fluid with alcohol -- being a  low-surface-tension liquid -- permitted the clay to be dried as a fine powder  rather than as hard lumps in the case of drying from water (El Rayah and  Rowell, 1973). Ca/Na mixed-ion clay was prepared by mixing dry Ca- and  Na-clay at a weight ratio of 7:3. Sand- (20--200 pm e.s.d.) and silt- (2--20 gm  e.s.d.) sized quartz particles were separated from silica flour by gravity  sedimentation. Each clay species at six levels (5%, 10%, 20%, 40%, 60%,    45    80%) were crossed with seven levels of skeletal grains (sand:silt ratios of sand  only (s), 4:1, 2:1, 1:1, 1:2, 1:4, silt only (z)}. The well-mixed samples were  placed into receptacles which were aluminium rings 1 cm internal diameter  and 1 cm tall, with one end closed by a piece of nylon cloth fixed in position  by rubber bands. The samples were equilibrated to pF zero over saturated  plastic foam with deionized water for two weeks. Additional samples at a  sand:silt ratio of 1:1 were equilibrated with appropriate chloride solutions  at 10-4, 10-3, 10-2 and 10-1 molar concentrations to check the effects of  electrolytes. The samples were then air-dried, impregnated with Spurt resin  and thin-sectioned according to the method of Jim (1981).  Related distribution patterns and plasmic fabrics were described according  to Brewer (1964, 1974, 1979). Unless stated otherwise, f-members refer to  sand-sized grains and f-matrices refer to silt- and clay-sized grains. Coarse  porphyric fabric refers to the case with f-members surrounded by an f-matrix  made up of mainly silt-sized materials; and fine porphyric of mainly clay-  sized materials. Coarse and fine matrices are used in the sense of Bodman  and Constantin (1965), that is with the f-member and the f-matrix in  physical continuity, respectively. Phyric RDP is used after Eswaran et al.  (1972).  Every sample was duplicated, and point-counting provided replicated  quantitative data on the relative proportions of micromorphological compo-  nents (Chayes, 1956; Anderson and Binnie, 1961; Eswaran, 1968).    RESULTS AND DISCUSSION    Ca-mon tmorillonite    The results of the experimentally produced related distribution patterns  and plasmic fabrics using Ca-montmorillonite are given in Fig. 1.  (a) 5% clay. With 5% clay and where the skeletal grains are dominated by  one particle-size class (either of sand at s, 4:1, 1:4 or of silt z) a phyric RDP 