maining uncoated. Thus, this dominantly orthogranic chlamydic  intergrade is a mixed complex fabric with a subdominant orthogranic RDP.    48    It is thought that the relative absence of silt in the f-matrix results in the  mobilization of the clay on wetting and in its plastering onto the surfaces of  the sand grains. This orientation of groups of clay domains parallel to the  grain surfaces results from the drying down of the liquid/air interface as the  receding water menisci retreat away from the centre of pores towards the  sand grains.  From 4:1 to z, the plasmic fabric is mainly silasepic, again because the  orientation of clay domains is hampered by the boundary effect of fine silt.  Most of the clays occur as isotropic and undulic units which are small and  discrete, and form isolated fillings in the small voids between silt grains in  the silt and clay fine-matrix. The small quantity of visible clay represents  groups of clay domains that happen to be orientated in the right direction in  relation to the optical axis of the microscope to show birefringence. At s,  the absence of interference from silt allows preferred orientation of clay  domains around some sand grain surfaces and a modest development of  skelsepic fabric.  Despite the increase in clay content, the volume of both small and large  voids shows a slight increase at all s:z ratios. The formation of clay coatings  around grains slightly expands the bulk volume of the grain matrix and  hence creates more intergranular space. Thus, less clay is available to fill the  enhanced volume of intergranular voids. There is a slight increase in weak  vosepic plasma which is in fact due to grain coatings in simple packing voids.  At high s:z ratios, where the influence from silt is relatively small, the clay  at this 10% level on wetting and drying is actively involved in shaping the  microfabric.  (c) 20% clay. At 20% clay, coarse porphyric fabrics are formed from 1:1  to z. The f-matrix -- with more silt than clay -- is compact and the quantity  is sufficient to engulf the sand grains completely. Also, there is occasionally  some orientation of elongated silt grains around sand grains, indicating the  significance of the isotropic compressive stress of drying (Towner, 1961)  in organizing the microfabric. At 2:1, the f-matrix -- with nearly equal  quantities of silt and clay -- coats most sand-grain surfaces. Additionally,  short and wide braces are formed that are in physical continuity with the  coatings across intergranular spaces. Not much void space is left, and the  fabric formed is plectic porphyric (Fig. 3). The f-matrix is dynamic and  mobile enough upon wetting and drying to spread and organize itself around  the sand grains, but at 4:1 there is insufficient f-matrix material to form  wide braces. Instead, narrower bridges are formed that both link the sand  grains and tend to widen at their contacts to form iunctic porphyric fabric  (Fig. 4). At s, the clay forms continuous coatings around the sand grains  and the amount of clay is more than enough to coat all the grains. The  surplus forms short and narrow bridges between the grains, forming a mixed  complex iunctic-chlamydic fabric (Fig. 5).  From 1:2 to z, the plasmic fabric remains dominantly silasepic, though  there is a minor development of skelsepic features. At 1:1, there is some    49    Fig. 3. Sample with 20% Ca-clay and a sand:silt ratio of 2:1, showing plectic porphyric  RDP and inskelsepic plasmic fabric; the mobility of the f-matrix is enhanced by the  increasing amounts of clay and, as a result, intergranular braces are formed. The sample  also marks the transition between fine and coarse matrices. (Cross-polarized light, X 110.)    Fig. 4. Sample with 20% Ca-clay and a sand:silt ratio of 4:1, showing iunctic plectic  RDP and inskelsepic plasmic fabric; intergranular bridges are formed; and the coarse  matrix is established which leaves much interstitial areas empty. (Cross-polarized light,  10.)    50    Fig. 5. Sample with 20% Ca-clay and sand as the only skeletal grains, showing mixed com-  plex iunctic-chlamydic RDP and skelsepic plasmic fabric; virtually all the clay (f-matrix)  is associated with the surfaces of the sand grains to form relatively thick and continuous  free grain argillans; some clay forms narrow bridges between sand grains. (Cross-polarized  light, 110.)  incipient formation of plasma separations, which lead to a weak insepic  fabric, and this is accompanied by a stronger but very thin (&lt;2.5 pm)  expression of skelsepic plasma. Thus, with 20% clay, wetting and drying and  their associated stresses result in the organization of clay domains. With  increasing amounts of sand, the plasmic fabric changes to inskelsepic at 2:1  and 4:1, as skelsepic features take precedence over insepic. With this increase  in the c:z ratio, the extra clay is associated with the sand-grain surfaces (Figs.  3 and 4). Eventually at s, the plasmic fabric becomes overwhelmingly  skelsepic as all the surfaces of the sand grains are covered by birefringent  clay, some being over 2.5 ~m thick (Fig. 5).  The volume of voids is lower than that at 10% clay, and the proportion  that is vosepic increases from 2:1 to s. The higher 20%-clay content has  expanded the coarse matrix even further by coating the grains, while at the  same time there is an extra supply of clay available for the filling of inter-  stitial spaces. This now more than offsets the increase in void ratio due to  matrix expansion. The predominance of fine matrix at a s:z ratio of less  than 1:1 and of coarse matrix at more than 1:1 suggests that the void ratio  is at a minimum at 1:1 and increases in both directions towards z or s. This  is verified by the results obtained from point-counting.  (d) 40% clay.  At 40% clay, the f-matrix has a smooth appearance and    51    engulfs the sand grains to form a fine porphyric fabric. This is texturally  from 1:2 to z, whilst the decrease in the proportion of sand delays the estab-  lishment of a coarse matrix until 4:1. Instead of acting disruptively on clay  orientation, many of the silt grains now behave like sand grains as inert  islands in the f-matrix. At 4:1, the c:z ratio reaches 3.3, and with the belated  formation of a coarse matrix, the f-matrix organizes itself around the sand  grains~ covering their surfaces completely. In addition the extra amount of  clay forms wide braces connecting the sand grains and so forming a fine  matrix. Much of the intergranular space is filled, and the fabric formed is  mixed complex plectic-porphyric. At s, the f-matrix is made up exclusively  of clay. Here, because of the large simple packing voids of sand grains, the  coarse matrix is more open. The clay covers all the grain surfaces and links  them together in the form of braces, though leaving much void space vacant.  The fabric formed has plectic features which are more dominant than  porphyric, hence porphyric plectic.  The plasmic fabric changes drastically with the s:z ratio. Insepic is domi-  nant at z and 1:4, due to the presence of more silt than clay in the f-matrix.  Characteristically this interferes with clay orientation and domain align-  ment, both in the matrix and on grain surfaces. Mosepic begins to emerge  at 1:2, and is accompanied by increasing skelsepic features with changes in  the c:z ratio in favour of clay. At 1:1, skelmosepic is in evidence, and this is  replaced by moskelsepic at 2:1 as skelsepic features begin to dominate with  the increase in sand and concomitant decrease in silt content. This decrease  in silt reduces the disruptive effect on clay orientation, whereas the increase  in sand provides more sites for the development of skelsepic plasma, the  thickness of which tends to increase with the size of grains. Thus the gradual  increase in the expression of clay orientation at the clay/grain interface  occurring with the increase in the c:z ratio is accompanied by an increase  in the significance of oriented clay in the matrix from z to 2:1 {from insepic  to mosepic), followed by a decrease from 2:1 towards s {from mosepic back  to insepic). At 4:1, the changeover from fine to coarse matrix breaks the  continuity of the f-matrix, which then becomes isolated pockets in the  interstices of the sand grains, and allows domination of clay orientation  around sand grains, giving rise to inskelsepic fabric. At s, inskelsepic fabric is  also formed.  Normal shrinkage in the context of the bulk sample (Stirk, 1954; Yong  and Warkentin, 1975) in a coarse matrix sample is restricted, and shrinkage  limit is reached at a relatively high moisture content as soon as the coarse  particles are in contact. The entry of air into the voids at a moisture content  lower than the shrinkage limit implies that the effective isotropic stress due  to moisture suction is drastically reduced (Towner, 1961). On the other  hand, in samples with fine matrices (s:z &lt;2:1), shrinkage limits are at a  much lower moisture content, allowing stronger compressive stress of  suction to be exerted for a longer duration. This may explain the formation  of insepic rather than mosepic fabric in the f-matrix of the coarse matrix  samples.    52    The development of skelsepic plasma in a coarse matrix under the  isotropic stress of drying is also different from that in a fine matrix. In a  coarse matrix, relatively large and continuous air/water interfaces are devel-  oped in the niches of the intergranular voids when the sample is dried below  the shrinkage limit. With further removal of water, any clay present in the  voids is confined between two surfaces, namely the receding air/water inter-  face furnished by surface tension of water, and the stationary and rigid sand-  grain surface. The recession of the air/water interface therefore results in  compression with a dominant direction of strain perpendicular to the surface  of the sand grain. Both the degree of orientation and the thickness of  skelsepic plasma generated by this unidirectional stress are relatively en-  hanced. On the other hand, in a fine matrix, the unidirectional stress is  replaced by an overall compressive stress of the shrinking sample. Strain  occurring around and in the vicinity of the sand grains is concentrated in  the plasma because sand grains cannot be deformed. A clay which swells  more will have a greater total strain upon shrinkage and hence more signif-  icant development of skelsepic fabric. Also, swelling increases interparticle  distance which reduces both physical and physico-chemical resistance against  particle rearrangement. The presence of sand grains in a shrinking mass of  clay offers a larger passive volume and hence a greater disruption of the  otherwise uniform spatial distribution of strain than the presence of silt  grains, which allows greater concentration of strain on its surface and thicker  embedded grain argillans.  At 40% clay, the volume of voids decreases from z towards 2:1, and this  marks the minimum void ratio characteristic of the transition between fine  and coarse matrices. In the fine matrix, all the voids are small due to the  packing of fine materials, and this contrasts with the dominant large voids  of the coarse matrix.  (e) 60% and 80% clay. At 60%, all seven s:z samples have more clay than  silt in the f-matrix which surrounds sand grains completely and forms a fine  porphyric fabric. Silt grains are also embedded by clay and can also be  regarded as f-members. The low content of grains ensures that no voids  (observable} are left unfilled by the f-matrix and that no coarse matrix can  be developed. Fine matrix also dominates at 80% clay and results in the same  monotonous fine porphyric fabric. The only variation across s:z samples is  the size of the inert embedded grains.  The plasmic fabrics are similarly homogeneously skelmasepic from s to  1:4 at both 60% and 80% clay levels. The dominance of masepic over  skelsepic is caused by the large proportion of plasma in relation to grains,  rather than by a reduction in the ability of the plasma to form embedded  grain argillans. In fact, all the sand grains have coatings of clay with skelsepic  fabric (neostrain), and the thickness of birefringent coatings is greater than  that of their counterparts at lower clay contents. About half of the coatings  have a maximum thickness over 2.5 pm. Also, because the coatings are  better developed on sand than on silt grains, the degree of skelsepic expres-  sion increases with the proportion of sand in the samples.    53    The strong development of skelsepic plasma reflects the large shrink/swell  potential of the samples and the resulting concentration of more strain on  a grain of a given size in comparison with the conditions at lower clay  contents. The stronger development of masepic fabrics also suggests a greater  total strain.  At z, mamosepic fabrics are formed at both 60% and 80% clay levels.  Failure to develop a significant skelsepic fabric is due to the small size of silt  grains which concentrates less strain and to the boundary effect of fine silt.  As a result, mosepic and masepic fabrics formed by isotropic compression  of a shrinking plasma dominate.  Most of the plasma separations constituting the masepic fabric are less  than 20 pm long and more than half are narrow (&lt; 2.5 pm). Such relatively  weak expression of masepic fabric is expected from a non-shearing develop-  ment  of plasma separation by isotropic compression mainly during  shrinkage. Furthermore, the masepic fabric tends to become less developed  at 80% than at 60% clay. It is thought that the presence of a certain number  of skeletal grains in addition to a sufficient amount of clay is required for  the development of masepic fabric by isotropic compression. The mechani-  cally inert grains in the dynamic and somewhat mobile clay matrix upset the  otherwise homogeneous stress distribution and result in localized uneven  strain in areas between grains. At an optimum grain content, which differs  according to the state of stress, masepic fabric by isotropic compression will  be best developed.  At 60% clay, the visible volume of voids in samples from 1:2 to z is  reduced to a very low percentage ranging from 4% to 10%. The 15%--30%  void volume at s and 4:1 consists of predominantly small voids (longest axis  &lt; 30 pm), and this illustrates the domination of the fine matrix. At 80%  clay, the volume of visible voids drops to a mere 1%--3%, and these are all  small and non-vosepic.    Ca/Na-montmorillonite    Only four levels of clay at 20%, 40%, 60% and 80% are investigated,  and the results of their experimentally produced RDP and plasmic fabrics  are illustrated in Fig. 6. As expected, at the lower clay contents of 5% and  10%, the fabric is controlled by skeletal gains to the virtual exclusion of  the clay. In comparison with the less active Ca-montmorillonite samples, the  greater swelling potential, water retention capacity and high plasticity index  of Ca/Na-clay (with sodium on the exchange complex equivalent to an  exchangeable sodium percentage of 30%) is expected to result in more intense  reorganization of their microfabrics.  (a) 20% clay.  At 20% clay, a coarse porphyric fabric is developed from  1:1 up to z. This is the same as for the Ca-montmorillonite samples but, at  2:1, iunctic porphyric instead of plectic porphyric is formed. More swelling  must have occurred in the Ca/Na-clay and this pushes the sand grains further    54    CLAY    +-+ + ++ -~    ,~?oIs~      ~?olN~oN~    o1~\~    Is~           ~c9oIs~  ?" 15~"    +?'C'~ t s~".-e " \~? I s%'~-+c~\~                +c?    +~9 IS'~              +      +        +        +      +          S  /            +       +         +         +       +            \    SAND                                                                SILT    Fig. 6. Related distribution pattern (RDP) and plasmic fabrics