BUTION PATTERNS    From the result of the experiments, relationships between RDP and  texture can be generalized into textural regions as shown in Fig. 13. Within  the given range of texture in each region is shown the most likely RDP -- the  modal fabric -- that would develop under the influence of the universal  process of wetting and drying and those, by analogy, to be expected in  soil microfabrics. There is, however, one proviso and that is that the strain  is isotropic. This results when there is no shear stress or too little to cause  any shearing. Intergrade fabrics would be expected to occur at transitional  areas adjacent to the demarcation lines. Where there are relatively large and    CLAY    fPo    Ch    Iu    Og    cPo    SAND                                                                SILT    Fig. 13. Generalized relationship between texture and related distribution pattern (RDP)  of samples subjected to isotropic stresses of wetting and drying. Arrows indicate the  likely movement of boundaries with increase in the activity of the clay fraction.    60    separable discrete areas with different textures, heterogeneous particle-size  distribution would create separated complexes, and mixed complexes where  there is intimate mixing of areas with different textures that cannot be  discretely separated (Brewer and Pawluk, 1975).  Orthogranic and phyric fabrics occupy the two 100% sand and silt apices,  respectively. The rest of the textural triangle is taken up mainly by  porphyric fabrics: coarse porphyric with a low clay content where both silt  and clay make up the f-matrix, and fine porphyric with a high clay content  where the f-matrix is dominated by clay with the role of silt becoming  that of f-members like sand. Around 100% clay, the fabric is predominantly  made up of plasma which can better be described as argillamatric (Eswaran,  1972), rather than fine porphyric. The role of plasma in RDP formation in  these fabric regions is largely passive.  A continuous fine matrix, which is the prerequisite for porphyric fabric,  is developed from 0% up to about 45% sand, above which it is supplanted by  coarse matrix. At low sand:silt ratio, the transition occurs at a higher sand  content ranging from 45% to 65% due to a dominantly silty f-matrix. This  implies that a lesser amount by weight of f-matrix material is required to  keep the sand grains apart. With little clay in the f-matrix, the loose packing  of the silt grains is the cause of its enhanced specific volume. Without  active plasma, the shrink/swell potential of the sample is extremely limited,  and the corollary is that only limited particle rearrangement towards closer  packing can occur. Also the binding effect of clay on grains which may  otherwise hold the silt grains closer together, is lacking. Hence, a relatively  small number of silt grains can keep a relatively large amount of sand from  establishing contact and can maintain a fine porphyric fabric at sand con-  tents &gt; 50%.  Coupled with a relatively low silt and clay content, the formation of  coarse matrix at high sand content allows the clay to play an active role  in moulding RDP. The majority of fabric variations, therefore, occur in  this part of the textural triangle where interfacial phenomena are significant.  Low clay content ensures that the intergranular voids are not completely  filled, whereas low silt content results in less disruption to clay organization.  In comparative terms, swelling and shrinkage and the associated particle  rearrangement are maximized in the niches of the relatively large voids.  Drying entails the recession of a relatively large and continuous air/water  interface away from the centre of the voids towards the sand-grain surfaces,  and in the process compresses the f-matrix materials onto the sand-grain  surfaces. The mobility of the f-matrix governs the extent and the forms of  the distribution on the sand grains. More silt than clay in the f-matrix  reduces its mobility and leads to a higher concentration around areas where  the intergranular distances are the least. More clay than silt, on the contrary,  enhances mobility and permits a more even spreading of the f-matrix onto  the sand grains. The former (high sand:silt ratio) creates dominantly bridges  linking sand grains: fabrics belonging to the iunctic sequence; the latter    61    (low sand:silt ratio) creates dominantly coatings around sand grains: fabrics  belonging to the chlamydic sequence.  In the iunctic sequence, an increase in the amount of f-matrix widens the  bridges and reduces the volume of voids such that the fabric grades towards  porphyric iunctic, then iunctic porphyric, until eventually the fine matrix is  established. As the f-matrix has more silt than clay, the coarse porphyric  fabric marks one end of the iunctic sequence. In the case of the chlamydic  sequence, an increase in the amount of f-matrix thickens the clay coatings on  sand grains, which merge, while still keeping the intergranular distance short  to form plectic fabric. Further increase builds up the volume of the f-matrix  at the expense of the voids such that the fabric grades into plectic porphyric  until the f-matrix is established. More clay than silt in the f-matrix then  creates a fine porphyric fabric.  The overall results of the present experiments agree to a large extent  with the detailed empirical observations on the broad relationships between  texture and fabrics in Australian (Brewer, 1979) and Canadian (McKeague  and Guertin, 1982) soils. The transition from coarse to fine matrix reported  by Brewer occurs at a much higher sand content (about 77%), suggesting that  the f-matrix has a more open structure and a larger specific volume than that  of the experimental materials reported here. The presence of inorganic as  well as organic binding agents that aggregate soils and stabilize them against  structural breakdown and pore collapse is a probable cause for the more  porous f-matrix.  An increase in the activity of the clay fraction can be expected to cause  changes in the RDP--texture relationship. In the present experiments, the  presence of sodium on the exchange complex enhances the activity of the  montmorillonite. Many of the changes occur at the boundaries between  coarse and fine matrices. The arrows in Fig. 13 summarize the directions of  displacement with increase in the activity of the clay. The transition from  coarse to fine porphyric fabrics can be interpreted as resulting from an  expansion of the coarse matrix due to the formation of thicker clay films  around sand grains, and consequently more f-matrix material is required to  establish a fine matrix. The transition is greater at higher clay content  because of the reduced development of clay coatings at low clay content.  The transition of the chlamydic towards the iunctic fabrics can be inter-  preted as resulting from the higher mobility of the f-matrix even at a relative-  ly low clay:silt ratio.    GENERAL DISCUSSION ON PLASMIC FABRIC    The generalized relationship between plasmic fabric and texture under the  influence of isotropic stresses of wetting and drying is summarized in  Fig. 14. Four regions can be recognized: (1) at very low clay content (&lt;10%)  plasmic fabric could not be assessed (not assessable), and at high silt content  silasepic (Si) fabric; (2) sepic fabric dominated by clay orientation around    62    CLAY    SkMa    Sk    Mo/Ma    IN    Si    Not Assessible    SAND                                                                SILT  Fig. 14. Generalized relationship between texture and plasmic fabric of samples subjected  to isotropic stresses of wetting and drying. Arrows indicate the likely movement of  boundaries with increase in the activity of the clay fraction.    sand grains (Sk); (3) sepic fabric dominated by clay orientation in the matrix  (In and Mo/Ma); (4) sepic fabric transitional between the last two (SkMa).  Contrary to RDP, much of the variation in plasmic fabric occurs on the  right-hand side in samples with low s:z ratios.  At low clay contents, silty samples understandably develop silasepic fabric  because of the dominating disruptive influence on clay orientation by silt.  Clay domains are scattered in the interstices or form very thin and hardly  perceptible coatings on silt grains. Plasma separations, which require at least  a partly continuous and dominantly clayey matrix to form, are therefore  absent. The percentage clay limit of silasepic fabric is higher at high silt  content and decreases with the increase in s:z ratio due to the gradual  decline in silt interference.  Samples with high sand content are dominated by skelsepic fabric from  about 10% to 50% clay. The coarse nature of these matrices results in the  reorganization of plasma on sand-grain surface and is better developed in  regions corresponding to chlamydic fabrics and less in iunctic fabrics. A  number of fine porphyric fabrics develop a dominant skelsepic fabric which    63    consists of embedded grain argillans rather than free grain argillans. The clay  content in this region is sufficient to form prominent skelsepic features but  not enough for prominent clay orientation in the matrix.  An increase in clay content in samples with low s:z ratios results in a  transition from silasepic to insepic fabric, with some incipient development  of small and randomly scattered plasma separations due to the increase in  c:z ratio. The changeover occurs at around 25% clay for samples with s:z  less than 1:2, and at around 18% clay for samples with s:z ranging from 1:2  to 2:1, indicating the effect of silt on clay orientation. In contrast, over a  similar range of clay content, the sandy samples maintain skelsepic fabrics.  Further increase in clay content in the silty region (fight-hand side of  Fig. 14) results in a transition to mosepic and weak masepic fabrics. Again,  the changeover is retarded till a higher clay content in samples with low s:z  ratios. The development of stronger sepic plasmic fabrics in the matrix  reflects the emergence of clay as the dominant particle-size fraction. The  expression of masepic features is always subordinate to those of mosepic in  this fabric region, especially in samples with a lower clay content.  At clay contents of more than 50% where the RDP is overwhelmingly fine  porphyric, samples from s to 1:4 give way to a dominantly masepic fabric  with subordinate skelsepic features. In samples with silt as the only skeletal  grains, a marked development of skelsepic fabric is not possible and the  fabric grades into masepic with auxiliary mosepic components. The same is  true at around 100% clay, corresponding to argillamatric RDP (Eswaran,  1972) where the paucity of skeletal grain precludes any skelsepic features.  On the whole, masepic fabrics are only weakly expressed. The limited  capacity of the isotropic stress of wetting and drying to rearrange clay  domains into elongated plasma separation is obvious. During wetting, the  originally randomly oriented clay domains swell by imbibing interlamellar  water and push against each other, the overall effect of which is the forma-  tion of an open microstructure that maintains the relative positions of the  domains. The main source of the increase in void ratio comes from the  expansion of interdomainal voids (Quirk, 1978). These movements are  unlikely to cause significant preferred orientation of clay domains. On the  other hand, the compressive stress generated by virtue of moisture suction  upon drying can lead to pore collapse and some domain-alignment on a  limited scale, thus forming small plasma separations characteristic of insepic,  mosepic, and at best weak masepic fabrics. Thus, any well-developed masepic  fabric in soils is likely to be formed by processes in addition to wetting and  drying. The findings of Greene-Kelly and Mackney (1970) support this  conclusion. Thus, wetting and drying that extends into the high suctions can  cause some limited particle organization by aligning clay domains into  positions of minimum potential energy. But this rearrangement creates only  small plasma separations with preferred orientation within them but very  poorly amongst them. Also, the equilibrium positions in general are attained  and stabilized fairly quickly in one cycle of wetting and drying (Croney and    64    Coleman, 1954; Greene-Kelly and Mackney, 1970). Shearing of soils under  strong anisotropic stress is therefore required if large plasma separations  with strong preferred orientations are to be developed.  The increase in the activity of the clay fraction with a greater amount of  exchangeable sodium causes some minor shifts of the generalized boundaries  which are concentrated in samples with low s:z ratios in the matrix at low to  medium clay contents. Sandy and clayey samples are less affected. The  overall trend of plasma fabric change is one of expansion from stronger sepic  towards  weaker  sepic--skelmasepic  (SkMa)  towards  mosepic/masepic  (Mo/Ma), and from weak sepic towards asepic--insepic (In) towards silasepic  (Si). The skelmasepic (SkMa) and skelsepic (Sk) fabrics also occur more  frequently.    PEDOLOGICAL IMPLICATIONS    Eswaran and Banos (1976) proposed normal RDP for samples packed  simply according to their texture without any influence from the processes  of pedogenic reorganization. The present results deviate significantly from  their normal RDP, suggesting that wetting and drying by itself can be sub-  stantial agents for fabric development in soils. Thus, it is proposed to  describe fabrics that result from the interplay of texture and wetting and  drying under an overall isotropic stress regime as "erdic" (after the term  "erdefication", Conacher and Dalrymple, 1977). Thus "erdic fabric" is a  group name for the suite of fundamental RDPs and plasmic fabrics sum-  marized in Figs. 13 and 14.  Whereas the present investigation is confined to the lowest level of organi-  zation of soil materials between plasma and grains, White (1966, 1967)  recognizes the importance of texture in conjunction with soil moisture  changes in the formation of various field structural types. Swelling and  shrinkage of soils with a clay matrix are more likely to result in structural  peds macroscopically because the fabric units of the f-matrix have a physical  continuity which allows a large portion of volume changes to be trans-  mitted. If the clay has a large shrink/swell potential, the fine porphyric  fabric could generate considerable stress upon swelling to cause shearing  along planes oblique to the directions of principal stresses. These may  exceed the rupture limit at certain intervals and result in the formation of  interpedal voids of blocky or sphenoid structures. If the texture creates  coarse porphyric fabric, which has silt as the principal component of the  f-matrix and therefore has much lower shrink/swell potential and is less  prone to shearing, orthogonal tensile fractures created during shrinkage  may become the interpedal voids of columnar or prismatic structures (White,  1966, 1967). When the clay content or the activity of the clay fraction is too  low, structural formation can be hampered due to the lack of volume  change, thus resulting in massive or apedal soils.    65    Some soils with coarse matrix (iunctic and chlamydic sequences) have  inherently lower shrink/swell potential in comparison with soils with the  same clay content and the same activity but more silt and less sand in their  porphyric fabrics. Here, some of the swelling of the clay that is largely  trapped within the interstices of sand grains can be accommodated within  the intergranular voids instead of being spread, and normal shrinkage is  arrested as soon as the f-members have established contacts. Shrinkage limit  is likely to be fairly high because the voids between f-members are not  collapsible. The inability to build up swelling pressure required for oblique  shear planes (Knight, 1980; Spoor and Godwin, 1980) and the lack of large  shrinkage required for orthogonal fractures necessary for the development of  peds imply that structure development in soils with coarse matrix can at best  be weak. Where such developments exist, softs are more likely to be of a low-  stress shrinkage-induced type, such as columnar or prismatic, rather than the  high-stress swelling-induced types, such as blocky or sphenoid that are char-  acteristic of soils with high shrink/swell potential and particularly evident in  Vertisols.  The formation of oriented clay films around f-members in coarse matrix  fabrics may enhance swelling in so far as any volume change at intergranular  contacts may be readily transmitted. The small volume of clay that is  involved and the dissipation of swelling-emanated stresses by plastic  deformation of the clay coatings (the intergranular voids provide room for  relatively unobstructed deformation) limit its effectiveness. Intergranular  bridges in iunctic fabrics generally exert less influence on shrink/swell  potential due to the presence of more inert silt than clay.  The arrangement of particles into RDP characteristic of a given texture  at the lowest level of organization in response to moisture fluctuations is  likely to be permanent and irreversible (Croney and Coleman, 1954). Like-  wise, fabric anisotropy has been related to aggregate stability (Brewer and  Blackmore, 1956; Cagauan and Uehara, 1965; Camp and Gill, 1969; Blake  and Gilman, 1970). This is aided by bonding agents but, except for physico-  chemical bonding amongst skeletal grains and clay domains, these have not  been assessed in this experimental study of microfabrics. Thus, as noted  earlier, a differing degree of restriction on the freedom of fabric unit  reorganization under an overall isotropic stress regime on wetting and drying  occurs in some of the experimentally produced erdic fabrics as compared  with those described from soil B-horizons.  As pointed out by McKeague and Guertin (1982), fabric identification  and classification is a rather subjective and inconsistent exercise. The large  measure of agreement between microfabrics produced experimentally  with empirical observations from soft B-horizons, however, suggests that  experimental fabrics produced under controlled and reproducible conditions  as described here offers the opportunity to set up benchmark fabrics to serve  as standards.    66    CONCLUSIONS    Results of this experimental study show that under the influence of  wetting and drying, systematic and repetitive variations in related distribu-  tion pattern (RDP) and plasmic fabric are formed in relation to textural-  change -erdic-fabric. At low clay content {0%--10%), all microfabrics are the  result of packing of skeletal grains. At medium clay content (20--40%),  the dynamic clay--water interaction generates reorganization. Here, the  sand:silt ratio begins to exert its influence and determines the fine to coarse  matrix transition and the degree of clay orientation. A low ratio disturbs  clay orientation and favours the formation of a fine matrix. A high ratio  favours clay orientation and the formation of a coarse matrix. In addition,  the clay:silt ratio determines the mobility of the f-matrix, which is more  mobile at a high ratio. At high clay content (&gt;60%), a fine matrix is formed  regardless of the sand:silt ratio, and clay mobility is hardly affected by the  clay:silt ratio. Thus, most fabric changes occur at medium clay contents  where a variety of packing (fine to coarse matrix) and a range of f-matrix  mobility (which itself is a function of the clay:silt ratio) are possible. The  domination of skeletal grains and clay at low and high clay contents, re-  spectively, produce a much lower variety of fabrics. Important variations  in RDP occur at medium clay content with coarse matrix, where a high  clay:silt ratio allows spreading of the f-matrix evenly on sand grains to form  fabrics of the chlamydic sequence and a low ratio restricts the f-matrix  movement, allowing only the formation of bridges between grains character-  istic of the iunctic sequence. A receding air--water interface in the coarse  matrix leads to the development of strong free grain argillans, whereas in the  fine matrix the disruption of the strain homogeneity by mechanically inert  grains is the cause of embedded grain argillans. The weak masepic fabric  tends to be less developed and expressed with increase in clay content and  is ascribed to the lack of strain disturbance provided by the grains. Increased  activity of the clay fraction brings about some limited changes in micro-  fabric. The only type of sepic plasmic fabric that can be developed strongly  under isotropic stresses of wetting and drying, is skelsepic. Strong develop-  ment of plasma separations in the matrix of erdic fabrics must be either  inherited or caused by anisotropic stresses. It is hoped that this study will  lead to further experimental investigations of the relationship between  specific soil-forming processes and fabrics.    ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS    C.Y. Jim wishes to express his gratitude to the Commonwealth Scholar-  ship Commission for the provision of financial support which allowed him  to undertake postgraduate research at the University of Reading.    67    REFERENCES    Anderson, D.M. and Binnie, R.R., 1961. Modal analysis of soils. Soil Sci. Soc. Am. Proc.,  25: 499--503.  Bartelli, L.J. and Odell, R.T., 1960. Laboratory studies and genesis of a clay-enriched  horizon in the lowest part of the solum of some brunizem and gray-brown podzolic  soils in Illinois. Soil Sci. Soc. Am. Proc., 24: 390--395.  Blake, G.R. and Gilman, R.D., 1970. Thixotropic changes with ageing of synthetic soil  aggregates. Soil Sci. Soc. Am. Proc., 34: 561--564.  Bodman, G.B. and Constantin, G.K., 1